Outliers detection¶

There are many techniques for detecting outliers, we are going to use the KNN anomaly detection.

In this method, we first define the number of nearest neighbors (k) and then we calculate the distance between each data point and its k-th nearest neighbor. Data points that have a large distance to their k-th nearest neighbor are considered outliers.

In [10]:
# Define the number of nearest neighbors (k)
k = 5

# Calculate the distance to the k-th nearest neighbor for each data point
nbrs = NearestNeighbors(n_neighbors=k, algorithm='ball_tree').fit(X)
distances, indices = nbrs.kneighbors(X)

# Identify the rows with large distances to their k-th nearest neighbor as outliers
outliers = np.max(distances, axis=1) > np.percentile(np.max(distances, axis=1), q=95)
data_without_outliers = X

# Print the outliers
print("Outliers detected using k-NN method:")
for i, is_outlier in enumerate(outliers):
    if is_outlier:
        data_without_outliers = data_without_outliers.drop(i)
        print(f"Data example {i} is an outlier.")

num_outliers = np.sum(outliers)

STRATIFIED DATA¶

The StratifiedShuffleSplit is a method from the scikit-learn library used for splitting a dataset into train and test sets. It splits the data into train and test sets while preserving the percentage of samples for each target class.

So we stratify the sample ensuring that we have the same proportion of classes in one set as in the other.

K-FOLDS¶

As we need to perform cross-validation, we would need to set n_splits to a value greater than 1 to generate multiple random splits of the data, so we set n_splits to 10, it means that the dataset will be split into 10 different training and testing sets.

We set random_state to 0 (int) to ensure that the same random splits will be generated each time the code is run with the same dataset and parameters.

Finally, we keep a test_size of 0.2 what means that 20% of the data will be used for testing and 80% of the data will be used for training. We think it is an appropiate percentage for the dataset size.

In [13]:
# We set the following variables that we are going to use during the notebook
n_splits = 10
test_size = 0.2
test_size_red = 0.7
random_state = 0

    y_test_ss = y[test_index]
    
sss_red = StratifiedShuffleSplit(n_splits=n_splits,test_size=test_size_red, random_state=random_state)
ss_red = ShuffleSplit(n_splits=n_splits,test_size=test_size_red, random_state=random_state)

    X_train_sss_red = X_scaled[train_index,:]

    X_train_ss_red = X_scaled[train_index,:]

    y_test_ss_red = y[test_index]
In [15]:
def KNN_function(n_neighbors, weights, p, cv, stratify, Matrix):
    
    cv = cv
    
    if stratify == sss:
        X_train = X_train_sss
        y_train = y_train_sss
        X_test = X_test_sss
        y_test = y_test_sss
    elif stratify == ss:
        X_train = X_train_ss
        y_train = y_train_ss
        X_test = X_test_ss
        y_test = y_test_ss
    elif stratify == sss_red:
        X_train = X_train_sss_red
        y_train = y_train_sss_red
        X_test = X_test_sss_red
        y_test = y_test_sss_red
    else:
        X_train = X_train_ss_red
        y_train = y_train_ss_red
        X_test = X_test_ss_red
        y_test = y_test_ss_red
    
    miKNNC = KNeighborsClassifier()
    param_grid = {'n_neighbors':n_neighbors,'weights':weights,'p':p}
    miGSCV = GridSearchCV(estimator=miKNNC,param_grid=param_grid,scoring='accuracy',cv=cv)#, verbose = 2)
    miGSCV.fit(X_train,y_train)  
    
    miMejorModeloKNNStr_bestEstimator = miGSCV.best_estimator_
    miMejorModeloKNNStr_params = miGSCV.best_params_
    
    miMejorModeloKNNStr_bestEstimator.fit(X_train,y_train)
    
    y_pred = miMejorModeloKNNStr_bestEstimator.predict(X_test)
    
    print("The best model is the one that contemplates the following parameters:\n", miMejorModeloKNNStr_params)
    print("The accuracy is:", round(100*sum(y_pred==y_test)/len(y_test),10), '%')
    print("The best score is:", miGSCV.best_score_)
    
    if Matrix == True:
        #Confusion matrix
        plt = plot_confusion_matrix(miMejorModeloKNNStr_bestEstimator,X_test, y_test)
        if cv == 5 and stratify == sss:
            plt.ax_.set_title("Confusion matrix, using stratification and K-Fold Cross-Validation")
        elif cv == 5 and stratify == ss:
            plt.ax_.set_title("Confusion matrix, without stratification and K-Fold Cross-Validation")

Now, we are going to test the KNN function for different parameters. Changing the number of neighbors and the weights to see the difference between them.

'Uniform' weights is a simple weighting scheme where all data points are given equal weight in a model.

'Distance' weights assigns different weights to data points based on their distance from the decision boundary. The closer a data point is to the boundary, the greater its weight in the model.

One important parameter in distance metrics is the value of 'p', which determines the type of distance metric used. Firstly, we have assigned 2 what means that we are using the Eucliden distance.

After analyzing the results obtained, when fixing the number of neighbors and changing the weights, the same result is obtained. This is because it is a simple model where all the data is equally important, so it is not necessary to give it different weights. Therefore, we consider that using the 'uniform' weight is enough.

Regarding the results obtained with differents number of neighbors, we have the same results considering 3 and 5 neighbors. In general, increasing the number of neighbors used in a model can lead to a smoother decision boundary and reduce the impact of noise in the data. This lead us to a better performance and less overfitting. However, increasing the number of neighbors can also reduce the model's sensitivity to local patterns in the data, which may be important for some applications.

Therefore, to find the best estimation, we are going to perform a Grid Search taking into account different numbers of neighbors, weights and distances.

LEAVE ONE OUT¶

Leave-One-Out (LOO) is a cross-validation technique where the model is trained on all the samples in the dataset except one, which is left out for testing. This process is repeated for each sample in the dataset, so that each sample is used as a test set exactly once. The LOO technique is often used for small datasets, where there are only a few samples available for training and testing.

Now, we are going to test the KNN function using the LeaveOneOut() function.

In [28]:
LOO_GSCV = KNN_function([1,3,5,7,9,11,13],['uniform','distance'],[2,3,4,5], LeaveOneOut(), sss, False)

The best model is the one that contemplates the following parameters:
 {'n_neighbors': 7, 'p': 2, 'weights': 'uniform'}
The accuracy is: 97.3684210526 %
The best score is: 0.9692307692307692

Comments¶

Dataset Accuracy Score
Original 98.2456140351 0.964835164835165
Without outliers 97.3684210526 0.9692307692307692

With the results obtained for both K-Folds and LOO cases, we obtain a greater precision using K-Folds compared to LOO despite the fact that the score obtained for LOO is slightly higher than for cross validation, 0.9648 and 0.9692 respectively.

We notice that when running the grid search in both cases, CV is slightly faster than LOO, since it involves fewer iterations.

Likewise, due to the score result obtained, LOO is more reliable since it is a small dataset and uses all the data for training and testing.

Confusion Matrix¶

The best way to interpret the results is the confusion matrix, where we can explore which classes are worst classified and react accordingly. A confusion matrix is a table that summarises the performance of a classification model by comparing the predicted labels of the model with the actual labels in the data.

    y_test_ss_dec = y[test_index]

def KNN_Reduced(n_neighbors, weights, p, cv, stratify, Matrix):   
    
    if stratify == sss:
        X_train = X_train_sss_dec
        y_train = y_train_sss_dec
        X_test = X_test_sss_dec
        y_test = y_test_sss_dec
    else:
        X_train = X_train_ss_dec
        y_train = y_train_ss_dec
        X_test = X_test_ss_dec
        y_test = y_test_ss_dec
        
    miKNNC = KNeighborsClassifier()
    param_grid = {'n_neighbors':n_neighbors,'weights':weights,'p':p}
    miGSCV = GridSearchCV(estimator=miKNNC,param_grid=param_grid,scoring='accuracy',cv=5)#, verbose = 2)
    miGSCV.fit(X_train,y_train)
        
    miMejorModeloKNNNonStr_bestEstimator = miGSCV.best_estimator_
    miMejorModeloKNNNonStr_params = miGSCV.best_params_
    
    miMejorModeloKNNNonStr_bestEstimator.fit(X_train,y_train)
    
    y_pred = miMejorModeloKNNNonStr_bestEstimator.predict(X_test)
    

    print("The best model is the one that contemplates the following parameters:\n", miMejorModeloKNNNonStr_params)
    print("The accuracy is:", round(100*sum(y_pred==y_test)/len(y_test),10), '%')
    print("The best score is:", miGSCV.best_score_)
    
    if Matrix == True:
        #Confusion matrix
        plt = plot_confusion_matrix(miMejorModeloKNNNonStr_bestEstimator,X_test, y_test)
        if cv == 5 and stratify == sss:
            plt.ax_.set_title("Confusion matrix, using stratification and K-Fold Cross-Validation")
        elif cv == 5 and stratify == ss:
            plt.ax_.set_title("Confusion matrix, without stratification and K-Fold Cross-Validation")
